```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{arrows.meta}

\begin{document}

\begin{tikzpicture}[
  node distance=1.8cm,
  every node/.style={draw, ellipse, minimum width=1.5cm, minimum height=0.8cm},
  arrow/.style={->, >=Stealth, semithick}
]

% Nodes
\node (type) at (0,0) {Type};
\node (size) at (-3,-1.5) {Size};
\node (weight) at (-1,-1.5) {Weight};
\node (texture) at (1,-1.5) {Texture};
\node (rigidity) at (3,-1.5) {Rigidity};
\node (gripper) at (-1.5,-3) {Gripper};
\node (target) at (1,-3) {Target};
\node (success) at (3,-4.5) {Success};
\node (robot) at (-1.5,-4.5) {Robot};
\node (goal) at (0.5,-4.5) {Goal};

% Edges/Arrows
\draw[arrow] (type) -- (size);
\draw[arrow] (type) -- (weight);
\draw[arrow] (type) -- (texture);
\draw[arrow] (type) -- (rigidity);
\draw[arrow] (size) -- (gripper);
\draw[arrow] (weight) -- (gripper);
\draw[arrow] (texture) -- (gripper);
\draw[arrow] (rigidity) -- (gripper);
\draw[arrow] (gripper) -- (target);
\draw[arrow] (target) -- (success);
\draw[arrow] (robot) -- (gripper);
\draw[arrow] (goal) -- (success);

\end{tikzpicture}

\end{document}
```

This code creates a directed graph with elliptical nodes representing the variables (Type, Size, Weight, Texture, Rigidity, Gripper, Target, Success, Robot, and Goal) and arrows showing the causal relationships between them. The layout matches the image with Type at the top, flowing down to the other variables, with Gripper being influenced by multiple factors and ultimately connecting to Target and Success.

